window.NETPLUS_LESSONS_W1 = {"1":{"title":"What is Networking?","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"1\" data-day=\"1\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 1 · Day 1</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">What is Networking?</h2></header><h3>Lesson Objectives</h3>\n<p>By the end of this lesson, students should be able to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Define a computer network</li>\n<li>Explain why networks are important</li>\n<li>Identify common networked devices</li>\n<li>Differentiate between the Internet, intranet, and local networks</li>\n<li>Explain how data moves between devices</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Introduction to Networking</h2>\n<p>A computer network is a group of devices connected together so they can communicate and share resources.</p>\n<p>Networks exist everywhere:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Homes</li>\n<li>Schools</li>\n<li>Businesses</li>\n<li>Hospitals</li>\n<li>Government agencies</li>\n<li>Data centers</li>\n<li>Mobile phone systems</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Examples of networked devices include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Desktop computers</li>\n<li>Laptops</li>\n<li>Smartphones</li>\n<li>Tablets</li>\n<li>Printers</li>\n<li>Servers</li>\n<li>Gaming consoles</li>\n<li>Smart TVs</li>\n<li>IoT devices</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Without networks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>File sharing would be difficult</li>\n<li>The Internet would not exist</li>\n<li>Cloud storage would not function</li>\n<li>Online gaming would not work</li>\n<li>Email would not function</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Why Networking Matters</h2>\n<p>Modern society depends heavily on networking.</p>\n<h3>Networking allows:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Communication</li>\n<li>Collaboration</li>\n<li>Remote access</li>\n<li>Cloud computing</li>\n<li>Video streaming</li>\n<li>Online learning</li>\n<li>E-commerce</li>\n<li>Cybersecurity monitoring</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Businesses rely on networking for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Employee communication</li>\n<li>Server access</li>\n<li>Database management</li>\n<li>VoIP phone systems</li>\n<li>Wireless access</li>\n<li>File storage</li>\n<li>Remote work</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Types of Networks</h2>\n<h3>LAN — Local Area Network</h3>\n<p>A LAN connects devices within a small area.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Home network</li>\n<li>School lab</li>\n<li>Office building</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Characteristics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>High speed</li>\n<li>Short distance</li>\n<li>Usually privately owned</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>WAN — Wide Area Network</h3>\n<p>A WAN connects multiple LANs across large distances.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The Internet</li>\n<li>Corporate branch offices</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Characteristics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Long-distance communication</li>\n<li>Uses ISP infrastructure</li>\n<li>Typically slower than LANs</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>MAN — Metropolitan Area Network</h3>\n<p>A MAN covers a city or large campus.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>University campus network</li>\n<li>Municipal government network</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>PAN — Personal Area Network</h3>\n<p>Small network around a person.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Bluetooth headphones</li>\n<li>Smartwatch syncing</li>\n<li>Phone hotspot</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Key Networking Terms</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Definition</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Node</td>\n<td>Any device connected to a network</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Packet</td>\n<td>Unit of transmitted data</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bandwidth</td>\n<td>Maximum data transfer rate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Latency</td>\n<td>Delay in communication</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Throughput</td>\n<td>Actual data transfer speed</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>ISP</td>\n<td>Internet Service Provider</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>NIC</td>\n<td>Network Interface Card</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>How Devices Communicate</h2>\n<p>Basic communication process:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Device creates data</li>\n<li>Data is broken into packets</li>\n<li>Packets travel across network devices</li>\n<li>Destination receives packets</li>\n<li>Packets are reassembled</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p>When loading a website:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Browser sends request</li>\n<li>DNS resolves website name</li>\n<li>Data travels through routers</li>\n<li>Server responds</li>\n<li>Webpage loads</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Introduction to Cisco Packet Tracer</h2>\n<p>Cisco Packet Tracer is a virtual networking simulator.</p>\n<p>Students will use it to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Build networks</li>\n<li>Configure routers</li>\n<li>Configure switches</li>\n<li>Test connectivity</li>\n<li>Troubleshoot problems</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Basic Interface Areas</h3>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Area</th>\n<th>Purpose</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Device List</td>\n<td>Select devices</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Workspace</td>\n<td>Build topology</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Simulation Mode</td>\n<td>Watch packets move</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>CLI Window</td>\n<td>Configure devices</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Practice Questions</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What is the difference between a LAN and WAN?</li>\n<li>Why are packets used instead of sending all data at once?</li>\n<li>What device allows computers to connect to a network?</li>\n<li>What is throughput?</li>\n<li>Why is networking important for businesses?</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h2>Homework</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Research your home network</li>\n<li>Identify all devices connected to Wi-Fi</li>\n<li>Draw a simple diagram showing how they connect</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 1, Day 1</strong> (What is Networking?), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Introduction to networks, the Internet, and why networking matters. Course expectations and Packet Tracer setup.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>What is Networking?</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which OSI layer is responsible for framing and MAC addresses?</li><li>What PDU is used at the transport layer?</li><li>Name one difference between the Internet and an intranet.</li><li>Which topology has a single point of failure at the center device?</li><li>What tool in Packet Tracer shows whether a ping succeeded in simulation mode?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> 10-question quiz covering OSI layer names, functions, and matching protocols to layers.</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Draw and label a home network diagram identifying at least 3 devices and which OSI layers they operate at.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Build a simple 3-PC star topology. Connect devices, assign IPs, and verify connectivity with ping in simulation mode.</p>\n</section></article>"},"2":{"title":"OSI Model Layers 1–3","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"1\" data-day=\"2\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 1 · Day 2</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">OSI Model Layers 1–3</h2></header><h2>Lesson Objectives</h2>\n<p>Students should be able to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Explain the purpose of the OSI model</li>\n<li>Identify Layers 1–3</li>\n<li>Describe functions of each layer</li>\n<li>Differentiate MAC and IP addresses</li>\n<li>Explain frames and packets</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>What is the OSI Model?</h2>\n<p>The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model is a conceptual framework used to understand how data travels through a network.</p>\n<p>The OSI model has 7 layers.</p>\n<p>Each layer performs a specific job.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Why the OSI Model Matters</h2>\n<p>The OSI model helps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Troubleshoot networks</li>\n<li>Standardize communication</li>\n<li>Understand protocols</li>\n<li>Design networks</li>\n<li>Isolate problems</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Layer 1 — Physical Layer</h2>\n<h3>Purpose</h3>\n<p>Handles physical transmission of bits.</p>\n<h3>Examples</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Ethernet cables</li>\n<li>Fiber optic cables</li>\n<li>Wireless radio waves</li>\n<li>Hubs</li>\n<li>Repeaters</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Responsibilities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Signaling</li>\n<li>Cable standards</li>\n<li>Connectors</li>\n<li>Voltage levels</li>\n<li>Bit transmission</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Common Standards</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Ethernet</li>\n<li>Fiber optics</li>\n<li>Wi-Fi radio frequencies</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Layer 2 — Data Link Layer</h2>\n<h3>Purpose</h3>\n<p>Controls node-to-node communication.</p>\n<h3>Key Concepts</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>MAC addresses</li>\n<li>Frames</li>\n<li>Error detection</li>\n<li>Switching</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Devices</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Switches</li>\n<li>Bridges</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>MAC Address</h3>\n<p>A MAC address is a physical hardware address.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p>00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E</p>\n<p>Characteristics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>48-bit hexadecimal</li>\n<li>Burned into NIC</li>\n<li>Used locally on LAN</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Frames</h2>\n<p>At Layer 2, data becomes a frame.</p>\n<p>A frame contains:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Source MAC</li>\n<li>Destination MAC</li>\n<li>Payload</li>\n<li>Error-checking information</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Layer 3 — Network Layer</h2>\n<h3>Purpose</h3>\n<p>Handles logical addressing and routing.</p>\n<h3>Main Responsibilities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>IP addressing</li>\n<li>Routing</li>\n<li>Packet forwarding</li>\n<li>Path selection</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Devices</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Routers</li>\n<li>Layer 3 switches</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Protocols</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>IPv4</li>\n<li>IPv6</li>\n<li>ICMP</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>IP Addresses</h2>\n<p>IP addresses identify devices logically.</p>\n<p>Example IPv4:</p>\n<p>192.168.1.10</p>\n<p>Unlike MAC addresses:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>IP addresses can change</li>\n<li>Used across networks</li>\n<li>Assigned manually or automatically</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Packet vs Frame</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Frame</th>\n<th>Packet</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Layer 2</td>\n<td>Layer 3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Uses MAC addresses</td>\n<td>Uses IP addresses</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Local delivery</td>\n<td>Network-wide delivery</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Encapsulation</h2>\n<p>As data moves down OSI layers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Headers are added</li>\n<li>Information changes form</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p>Data → Segment → Packet → Frame → Bits</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Practice Questions</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>What layer uses MAC addresses?</li>\n<li>What device operates at Layer 3?</li>\n<li>What is encapsulation?</li>\n<li>What is the role of the Physical Layer?</li>\n<li>Why are IP addresses needed?</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 1, Day 2</strong> (OSI Model Layers 1–3), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Physical, Data Link, and Network layers. Signal types, MAC vs IP addressing, basic frame structure.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>OSI Model Layers 1–3</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which OSI layer is responsible for framing and MAC addresses?</li><li>What PDU is used at the transport layer?</li><li>Name one difference between the Internet and an intranet.</li><li>Which topology has a single point of failure at the center device?</li><li>What tool in Packet Tracer shows whether a ping succeeded in simulation mode?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> 10-question quiz covering OSI layer names, functions, and matching protocols to layers.</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Draw and label a home network diagram identifying at least 3 devices and which OSI layers they operate at.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Build a simple 3-PC star topology. Connect devices, assign IPs, and verify connectivity with ping in simulation mode.</p>\n</section></article>"},"3":{"title":"OSI Model Layers 4–7","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"1\" data-day=\"3\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 1 · Day 3</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">OSI Model Layers 4–7</h2></header><h2>Layer 4 — Transport Layer</h2>\n<h3>Purpose</h3>\n<p>Ensures reliable or fast communication.</p>\n<h3>Protocols</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>TCP</li>\n<li>UDP</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>TCP</h2>\n<p>Transmission Control Protocol:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Reliable</li>\n<li>Connection-oriented</li>\n<li>Error checking</li>\n<li>Acknowledgments</li>\n<li>Slower</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Used for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Web browsing</li>\n<li>Email</li>\n<li>File transfers</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>UDP</h2>\n<p>User Datagram Protocol:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fast</li>\n<li>Connectionless</li>\n<li>No acknowledgments</li>\n<li>Lower overhead</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Used for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Streaming</li>\n<li>Gaming</li>\n<li>VoIP</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Ports</h2>\n<p>Ports identify services.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Port</th>\n<th>Service</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>80</td>\n<td>HTTP</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>443</td>\n<td>HTTPS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>53</td>\n<td>DNS</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>25</td>\n<td>SMTP</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>22</td>\n<td>SSH</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Layer 5 — Session Layer</h2>\n<p>Controls sessions between devices.</p>\n<p>Responsibilities:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Establish sessions</li>\n<li>Maintain sessions</li>\n<li>Terminate sessions</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Layer 6 — Presentation Layer</h2>\n<p>Responsible for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Encryption</li>\n<li>Compression</li>\n<li>Translation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>SSL/TLS</li>\n<li>JPEG</li>\n<li>ASCII</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Layer 7 — Application Layer</h2>\n<p>Closest to the user.</p>\n<p>Provides network services to applications.</p>\n<p>Protocols:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>HTTP</li>\n<li>HTTPS</li>\n<li>FTP</li>\n<li>DNS</li>\n<li>SMTP</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>OSI Mnemonic</h2>\n<p>Top to Bottom:</p>\n<p>All People Seem To Need Data Processing</p>\n<p>Bottom to Top:</p>\n<p>Please Do Not Throw Sausage Pizza Away</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Practice Activity</h2>\n<p>Match protocols to layers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>TCP</li>\n<li>IP</li>\n<li>Ethernet</li>\n<li>HTTP</li>\n<li>DNS</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 1, Day 3</strong> (OSI Model Layers 4–7), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Transport, Session, Presentation, Application layers. TCP vs UDP overview, ports introduction.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>OSI Model Layers 4–7</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which OSI layer is responsible for framing and MAC addresses?</li><li>What PDU is used at the transport layer?</li><li>Name one difference between the Internet and an intranet.</li><li>Which topology has a single point of failure at the center device?</li><li>What tool in Packet Tracer shows whether a ping succeeded in simulation mode?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> 10-question quiz covering OSI layer names, functions, and matching protocols to layers.</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Draw and label a home network diagram identifying at least 3 devices and which OSI layers they operate at.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Build a simple 3-PC star topology. Connect devices, assign IPs, and verify connectivity with ping in simulation mode.</p>\n</section></article>"},"4":{"title":"Network Types & Topologies","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"1\" data-day=\"4\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 1 · Day 4</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Network Types &amp; Topologies</h2></header><h2>Topologies</h2>\n<h3>Star Topology</h3>\n<p>All devices connect to central switch.</p>\n<p>Advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Easy troubleshooting</li>\n<li>Common today</li>\n<li>Reliable</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Disadvantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Switch failure impacts network</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Bus Topology</h3>\n<p>Single backbone cable.</p>\n<p>Advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cheap</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Disadvantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Difficult troubleshooting</li>\n<li>Backbone failure impacts all devices</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Ring Topology</h3>\n<p>Devices connected in circular path.</p>\n<p>Advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Predictable traffic flow</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Disadvantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Single failure may break ring</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Mesh Topology</h3>\n<p>Devices interconnected.</p>\n<p>Advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Redundancy</li>\n<li>Reliability</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Disadvantages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Expensive</li>\n<li>Complex</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Hybrid Topology</h3>\n<p>Combination of multiple topologies.</p>\n<p>Common in enterprises.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Wired vs Wireless Networks</h2>\n<h3>Wired Advantages</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Faster</li>\n<li>More secure</li>\n<li>Lower latency</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Wireless Advantages</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Mobility</li>\n<li>Convenience</li>\n<li>Easy deployment</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Real-World Examples</h2>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Network Type</th>\n<th>Example</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>LAN</td>\n<td>School lab</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>WAN</td>\n<td>Internet</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>PAN</td>\n<td>Bluetooth earbuds</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>MAN</td>\n<td>City government</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 1, Day 4</strong> (Network Types & Topologies), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>LAN, WAN, MAN, PAN. Star, mesh, bus, ring, and hybrid topologies with real-world examples.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Network Types &amp; Topologies</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which OSI layer is responsible for framing and MAC addresses?</li><li>What PDU is used at the transport layer?</li><li>Name one difference between the Internet and an intranet.</li><li>Which topology has a single point of failure at the center device?</li><li>What tool in Packet Tracer shows whether a ping succeeded in simulation mode?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> 10-question quiz covering OSI layer names, functions, and matching protocols to layers.</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Draw and label a home network diagram identifying at least 3 devices and which OSI layers they operate at.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Build a simple 3-PC star topology. Connect devices, assign IPs, and verify connectivity with ping in simulation mode.</p>\n</section></article>"},"5":{"title":"Packet Tracer Introduction Lab","html":"<article class=\"lesson-prose lh-lesson-body\" data-week=\"1\" data-day=\"5\"><header class=\"lesson-inline-header\"><span class=\"lesson-badge\">Week 1 · Day 5</span><h2 class=\"lesson-title\">Packet Tracer Introduction Lab</h2></header><h2>Lab Objectives</h2>\n<p>Students will:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Open Packet Tracer</li>\n<li>Add devices</li>\n<li>Connect cables</li>\n<li>Configure basic IP addresses</li>\n<li>Test connectivity using ping</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2>Lab Steps</h2>\n<h3>Step 1 — Add Devices</h3>\n<p>Add:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>1 switch</li>\n<li>3 PCs</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Step 2 — Cable Devices</h3>\n<p>Use Copper Straight-Through cables.</p>\n<p>Connect:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>PC0 → Switch</li>\n<li>PC1 → Switch</li>\n<li>PC2 → Switch</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h3>Step 3 — Configure IP Addresses</h3>\n<p>Assign:</p>\n<table class=\"data-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Device</th>\n<th>IP</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>PC0</td>\n<td>192.168.1.10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>PC1</td>\n<td>192.168.1.11</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>PC2</td>\n<td>192.168.1.12</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p>Subnet Mask:</p>\n<p>255.255.255.0</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Step 4 — Test Connectivity</h3>\n<p>Open Command Prompt.</p>\n<p>Use:</p>\n<p>ping 192.168.1.11</p>\n<p>Verify replies.</p>\n<hr>\n<h3>Step 5 — Simulation Mode</h3>\n<p>Observe packets moving.</p>\n<p>Watch:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>ARP requests</li>\n<li>ICMP packets</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<div class=\"lesson-expand\">\n<h3>Study deeper</h3>\n<p>Use this section with the reading above. For <strong>Week 1, Day 5</strong> (Packet Tracer Introduction Lab), focus on how the topic appears on the Network+ N10-009 exam: know definitions, compare similar terms, and tie concepts to a troubleshooting or design scenario.</p>\n<h4>Exam-style checkpoints</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>State the concept in one sentence without notes.</li>\n<li>Give one real-world example (home, school, or business).</li>\n<li>Name the tool, device, or protocol involved.</li>\n<li>Describe what breaks if this is misconfigured.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Packet Tracer tie-in</h4>\n<p>Open your lab file for this week and locate where this topic applies—routing table, VLAN, ACL, DHCP pool, or wireless settings. Change one setting, test with <code>ping</code> or <code>show</code> commands, then undo the change to confirm you understand cause and effect.</p>\n</div>\n<hr class=\"lesson-hr\"/>\n<section class=\"lesson-footer\">\n<h3>Today&apos;s focus</h3>\n<p>Hands-on orientation: placing devices, connecting cables, simulation mode.</p>\n<h3>Learning activities</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Skim the lesson once, then re-read while annotating terms you cannot define from memory.</li>\n<li>Draw a small diagram linking <strong>Packet Tracer Introduction Lab</strong> to the correct OSI layer(s) and devices.</li>\n<li>Answer the practice questions below closed-book, then check your notes.</li>\n<li>Spend 15–20 minutes in Packet Tracer applying one idea from this lesson.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Practice questions</h3>\n<ol class=\"lesson-practice-list\"><li>Which OSI layer is responsible for framing and MAC addresses?</li><li>What PDU is used at the transport layer?</li><li>Name one difference between the Internet and an intranet.</li><li>Which topology has a single point of failure at the center device?</li><li>What tool in Packet Tracer shows whether a ping succeeded in simulation mode?</li></ol>\n<h3>Homework</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Write a half-page summary of today&apos;s lesson in your own words (no copy-paste).</li>\n<li>Add three flashcards: term on front, definition and example on back.</li>\n<li>Connect one concept from today to this week&apos;s project or lab deliverable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>This week&apos;s assessments</h3>\n<p><strong>Mini quiz:</strong> 10-question quiz covering OSI layer names, functions, and matching protocols to layers.</p>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Draw and label a home network diagram identifying at least 3 devices and which OSI layers they operate at.</p>\n<p><strong>Packet Tracer lab:</strong> Build a simple 3-PC star topology. Connect devices, assign IPs, and verify connectivity with ping in simulation mode.</p>\n</section></article>"}};
